== International racing career ==
=== IAAF World Cross Country Championships ===
: [[1980 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|1980]] Junior Men's Individual Race - Bronze Medal
: [[1983 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|1983]] Men's Team Event: USA - Silver Medal
: [[1984 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|1984]] Men's Team Event: USA - Silver Medal
: [[1985 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|1985]] Men's Team Event: USA - Bronze Medal
: [[1986 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|1986]] Men's Team Event: USA - Bronze Medal

=== Olympic and International Distance Races ===
: [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics - Men's Marathon|Olympic Marathon 1988]] Seoul, Korea (29th place, 2:19:09)
: [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics - Men's Marathon|Olympic Marathon 1992]] Barcelona, Spain (13th place, 2:15:23)
: Personal Best Marathon: 2:10:59
: Personal Best 10,000 Meters 27:40<ref>[http://www.fasterrunning.com/oldsite/roadrecords.htm All Time Road Records<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
: Ranked in the <U+201C>Top Ten<U+201D> of US  Marathoners, for nine years.
: Ranked in the <U+201C>Top Ten<U+201D> of US 10,000 Meters for eight years.
: Five Time US Road Racer of the Year.
: 1st place, Bellin 10K Run (Green Bay, Wisc.), (1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995)
: 1st place, [[Bay to Breakers]], (San Francisco, Ca.) (1986)
: 1st place, [[Peachtree Road Race|Peachtree Road Race 10K]] (Atlanta, Ga.) (1991)
: 1st place, The Medical Center 10K Classc (Bowling Green, Ky.) (1990)<ref>[http://www.10k.bowlinggreen.net/results.html The Medical Center 10k Classic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
: 21st place, [[1995 World Championships in Athletics - Men's Marathon|World Championships in Athletics - Men's Marathon]] (1995)

==Post-racing career==
After putting up his shoes, Eyestone has become a noted distance and road racing expert, serving as a columnist for ''Runners World'' magazine and television commentor for ESPN's "Race of the Month" series. Eyestone served as an analyst for [[NBC Sports]] coverage of [[Track and Field]] and [[Race Walking]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref>[http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/mediumwell/blog/2008/07/your_nbc_olympics_lineup.html Medium Well: Your NBC Olympics lineup - A blog on sports media, news and networks - baltimoresun.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Eyestone returned to BYU as head coach of the cross-country team.<ref>[http://www.byucougars.com/StaffProfile.jsp?ID=46 BYUCougars.com - BYU Staff Profile (Ed Eyestone)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Eyestone is a three-time selection as "Coach of the Year" for the [[Mountain West Conference]] (MWC). Previously he served as assistant track coach at [[Weber State University]].  

